Suppose that those who take the treatment and those who do not are very much unlike each other, and yet the ways in which they differ are captured exhaustively by a set of observed treatment assignment and/or selection variables S.
For the language we will adopt in this module, knowledge and observation of S allow for a “perfect stratification” of the data. By “perfect,” we mean precisely that individual within groups defined by values of the variables in S are entirely indistinguishable from each other except for (i) observed treatment status, and (ii) differences in the potential outcomes that are independent of treatment status.
Under such perfect stratification, we would be able to assert Assumption 1-S: E[Y 1jD = 1; S] = E[Y 1jD = 0; S], and Assumption 2-S: E[Y 0jD = 1; S] = E[Y 0jD = 0; S]. These assumptions are sufficient to enable consistent and unbiased estimation of the ATE because the treatment can be considered to be (as good as) randomly assigned within groups defined by values of the variables in S.
